        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Independent peer review of FE input deck completed with all critical findings resolved; modelling protocol followed and checklist signed off by both primary analyst and reviewer."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "rationale": "A hyperelastic-plastic constitutive model (Ogden-Hill hybrid) was selected for UHMWPE based on published literature benchmarks and the material coupon validation (VR03). The femoral component was modelled as a rigid body, justified by the five-orders-of-magnitude stiffness differential between CoCr and UHMWPE. Frictionless and frictional (μ = 0.06) contact sensitivity runs confirmed peak stress sensitivity to friction < 4%, within model uncertainty bounds. Model form assumptions documented in the modelling assumptions register.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/tka-model-form-ac-10",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "Constitutive model validated against material coupon data with R² > 0.98; rigid body assumption for femoral component justified by stiffness ratio analysis; key model form assumptions documented and reviewed."
      }
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "rationale": "All model inputs were sourced from NIST-traceable measurements or peer-reviewed literature with documented uncertainty bounds. UHMWPE material parameters were derived from the coupon test campaign (n=8 specimens). Geometry was digitised from production CMM reports (tolerance ± 0.05 mm). Loading profiles were derived from ISO 14243-1 with force measurement uncertainty ± 1.5%. Input uncertainty distributions were propagated through the model via Monte Carlo simulation (n=5000) to produce prediction intervals on QoIs. Achieved level 3 through complete probabilistic input characterisation.",
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/ac/tka-model-inputs-ac-11",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "description": "All primary model inputs traceable to calibrated measurements or peer-reviewed sources; uncertainty bounds documented for each input; probabilistic propagation performed with n ≥ 1000 samples."
